lm_table Fit linear regressions by group, and get different output options.

Kevin Oâ€™Brien

27 November 2018

Description

With this function itÃ¢Â€Â™s possible to fit linear regressions by a grouping variable, and get a data frame with each column as a coefficient and quality of fit variables, and other output options. Works with dplyr grouping functions.

Usage


lm_table(df, model, .groups = NA, output = "table", est.name = "est",
keep_model = FALSE)

Arguments

df: A data frame. model: : A linear regression model, with or without quotes. The variables mentioned in the model must exist in the provided data frame. X and Y sides of the model must be separated by â€œ~â€. * .groups: Optional argument. Quoted name(s) of grouping variables used to fit multiple regressions, one for each level of the provided variable(s). Default NA. * output: Selects different output options. Can be either â€œtableâ€, â€œmergeâ€, â€œmerge_estâ€ and â€œnestâ€. See details for explanations for each option. Default: â€œtableâ€. * est.name : Name of the estimated y value. Used only if est.name = TRUE. Default: â€œestâ€. * keep_model : If TRUE, a column containing lm object(s) is kept in the output. Useful if the user desires to get more information on the regression.Default: FALSE.

Examples

library(forestmangr)
library(dplyr)

# Fit Schumacher and Hall model for volume estimation, and get coefficient, R2 and error values:
lm_table(exfm19, log(VWB) ~ log(DBH) + log(TH))
##          b0       b1          b2      Rsqr  Rsqr_adj Std.Error
## 1 -9.413899 1.912987 -0.08394832 0.3278838 0.3274628 0.7958599
# Fit SH model by group:
lm_table(exfm19, log(VWB) ~ log(DBH) + log(TH), "STRATA")
##   STRATA        b0       b1         b2      Rsqr  Rsqr_adj Std.Error
## 1      4 -9.863498 1.720963  0.2094430 0.2289023 0.2281178 0.8326625
## 2      2 -9.168058 2.005930 -0.2346844 0.4334018 0.4324760 0.7329438
# This can also be done using dplyr::group_by:
exfm19 %>%
group_by(STRATA) %>%
lm_table(log(VWB) ~ log(DBH) + log(TH) )
##   STRATA        b0       b1         b2      Rsqr  Rsqr_adj Std.Error
## 1      4 -9.863498 1.720963  0.2094430 0.2289023 0.2281178 0.8326625
## 2      2 -9.168058 2.005930 -0.2346844 0.4334018 0.4324760 0.7329438
# It's possible to merge the original data with the table containg the coefficients
# using the output parameter:
lm_table(exfm19, log(VWB) ~ log(DBH) + log(TH), "STRATA", output = "merge")

In the following example, the objective is to estimate non-measured height values in a forest inventory data. To do this, weâ€™ll fit a hypsometric model. The non-measured trees will be automatically ignored in this step. Weâ€™ll define the argument output as â€œmerge_estâ€, so that we can get the estimated height values as a separate column. Then, weâ€™ll use mutate to create a new variable, that will contain measured height values, along with estimated ones. To do this weâ€™ll use ifelse, and check for NAs inside the Height column. When it finds it, it will basically fill them with estimated values.

library(forestmangr)
library(dplyr)
data("exfm15")

head(exfm15, 20)
##    STRATA STRATA_AREA PLOT PLOT_AREA  DBH   TH OBS

ex_th_est <- exfm15 %>%
lm_table(log(TH) ~ inv(DBH),output = "merge_est" ) %>%
mutate( TH_EST = ifelse(is.na(TH), est, TH ) )
# Now we can see that the values were estimated successfully.

Details

With this function thereÃ¢Â€Â™s no more need to use the do function when fitting a linear regression in a pipe line. ItÃ¢Â€Â™s also possible to easily make fit multiple regressions, specifying a grouping variable. In addition to that, the default output sets each coefficient as a column, making it easy to call coefficients by name or position when estimating values. It iss possible to use the output argument to get a merged table if output=â€œmergeâ€, that binds the original data frame and the fitted coefficients. If output=â€œmerge_estâ€ we get a merged table as well, but with y estimated using the coefficients. If the fit is made using groups, this is taken into account, i.e.Â the estimation is made by group. If output=â€œnestâ€, a data frame with nested columns is provided. This can be used if the user desires to get a customized output.

Value

A data frame. Different data frame options are available using the output argument. ## Author(s) Sollano Rabelo Braga sollanorb@gmail.com
